04813nam a22006615i 9780520972155DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209721557 a10.1525/97805209721552doi  a(DE-B1597)534789  a(OCoLC)1079399644  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHN400.H84 7aHIS0150002bisacsh04a303.6/1223/eng1 aGrant, Kevin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLast Weapons :bHunger Strikes and Fasts in the British Empire, 1890–1948 /cKevin Grant. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBerkeley Series in British Studies ;v1600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Knowing Starvation: Science and Strange Stories -- t2. British Suffragettes and the Russian Method of Hunger Strike, 1890–1914 -- t3. A Shared Sacrifice: Hunger Strikes by Irish Women and Men, 1912–1946 -- t4. Building the Nation’s Temple: Hunger Strikes and Fasts by Nationalists in India, 1912–1948 -- t5. The Rule of Exceptions: Hunger Strikes and Political Prisoner Status in Britain, Ireland, and India, 1909–1946 -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLast Weapons explains how the use of hunger strikes and fasts in political protest became a global phenomenon. Exploring the proliferation of hunger as a form of protest between the late-nineteenth and mid-twentieth centuries, Kevin Grant traces this radical tactic as it spread through trans-imperial networks among revolutionaries and civil-rights activists from Russia to Britain to Ireland to India and beyond. He shows how the significance of hunger strikes and fasts refracted across political and cultural boundaries, and how prisoners experienced and understood their own starvation, which was then poorly explained by medical research. Prison staff and political officials struggled to manage this challenge not only to their authority, but to society’s faith in the justice of liberal governance. Whether starving for the vote or national liberation, prisoners embodied proof of their own assertions that the rule of law enforced injustices that required redress and reform. Drawing upon deep archival research, the author offers a highly original examination of the role of hunger in contesting an imperial world, a tactic that still resonates today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHunger strikeszGreat Britainy20th century. 0aHunger strikeszIndiay20th century. 0aHunger strikeszIrelandy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCA Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065207908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311066763940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520972155?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520972155423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520972155/original  a978-3-11-061017-8  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065207-9  UCA Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-0